	abstract = {The theory of binary evolution predicts that many massive stars should lose their hydrogen-rich envelopes via interaction with a companion -- revealing hot helium stars with masses of \${\textbackslash}sim\$2--8M\$\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}\$. However, only one candidate system had been identified, leaving a large discrepancy between theory and observation. Here, we present a new sample of stars -- identified via excess ultraviolet emission -- whose luminosities, colors, and spectral morphologies are consistent with predictions for the missing population. We detect radial velocity variations indicative of binary motion and measure high temperatures (\$T\_\{{\textbackslash}rm eff\}{\textbackslash}sim60-100\$kK), high surface gravities (\${\textbackslash}log(g){\textbackslash}sim5\$) and depleted surface hydrogen mass fractions (\$X\_\{{\textbackslash}rm\{H,surf\}\}{\textbackslash}lesssim0.3\$), which match expectations for stars with initial masses between 8--25 M\$\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}\$ that have been stripped via binary interaction. These systems fill the helium star mass gap between subdwarfs and Wolf-Rayet stars, and are thought to be of large astrophysical significance as ionizing sources, progenitors of stripped-envelope supernovae and merging double neutron stars.},
